WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:03.360
<v Teacher>You might have noticed that we're not using the word for I.

00:00:03.360 --> 00:00:06.080
<v Teacher>Quiero by itself means I want.

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:07.120
<v Teacher>There is a word for I.

00:00:07.120 --> 00:00:08.400
<v Teacher>The word for I is yo.

00:00:08.560 --> 00:00:10.160
<v Teacher>Y-o.

00:00:10.219 --> 00:00:10.860
<v Teacher>Yeah.

00:00:10.860 --> 00:00:13.420
<v Teacher>And you only use it if you want to be emphatic.

00:00:13.420 --> 00:00:18.220
<v Teacher>So if you want to say I want and show that emphasis, how would you do it?

00:00:19.019 --> 00:00:20.060
<v Teacher>Yo quiero.

00:00:20.060 --> 00:00:21.500
<v Teacher>Yo quiero.

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:23.500
<v Teacher>I don't want.

00:00:23.500 --> 00:00:24.779
<v Teacher>No iociero.

00:00:25.019 --> 00:00:26.539
<v Teacher>Same order as English.

00:00:26.539 --> 00:00:28.460
<v Teacher>I don't want.

00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:31.140
<v Student>Yo no quiero.

00:00:31.140 --> 00:00:31.540
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:31.540 --> 00:00:32.900
<v Teacher>Yo nociero.

00:00:32.900 --> 00:00:34.100
<v Teacher>I don't want.

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:34.739
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:34.739 --> 00:00:37.220
<v Teacher>I don't want to cancel.

00:00:37.739 --> 00:00:40.460
<v Student>Yo no quiero cancelar.

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:41.019
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:41.019 --> 00:00:43.579
<v Teacher>Yo no quiero cancelar.

00:00:43.899 --> 00:00:47.420
<v Teacher>How would you say celebration?

00:00:48.460 --> 00:00:49.820
<v Student>Celebracion.

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:51.020
<v Teacher>Celebracion.

00:00:51.020 --> 00:00:51.500
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:53.739
<v Teacher>And to celebrate?

00:00:53.739 --> 00:00:54.540
<v Student>Celebrar.

00:00:54.700 --> 00:00:55.500
<v Teacher>Celebrar.

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:57.420
<v Teacher>I want to celebrate.

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:00.879
<v Student>Quiero celebrar.

00:01:00.879 --> 00:01:02.640
<v Teacher>Quiero celebrar.

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:03.680
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.720
<v Teacher>What would it mean if I say quiero ilustrar?

00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:10.799
<v Teacher>Quiero ilustrar.

00:01:11.159 --> 00:01:12.920
<v Student>I want to illustrate.

00:01:12.920 --> 00:01:14.280
<v Teacher>Yes, I want to illustrate.

00:01:14.280 --> 00:01:16.200
<v Teacher>This is an interesting word as well actually.

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:20.280
<v Teacher>The the luz inside of illustrar means light.

00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:21.640
<v Teacher>And uh the word loos

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:33.000
<v Teacher>L-U-Z so actually the Z would be pronounced T in most of Spain, luz, but in the rest of Spanish speaking world luz means light, so you can use that word as well

00:01:33.240 --> 00:01:36.440
<v Teacher>How would you say I want to find out?

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:41.640
<v Teacher>Now in Spanish you will say something like I want to inform myself.

00:01:41.640 --> 00:01:43.640
<v Teacher>I want to inform myself

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:48.720
<v Teacher>Good, very good.

00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:50.240
<v Teacher>Quiero informarme.

00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:51.680
<v Teacher>So how was information

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:54.220
<v Teacher>Información.

00:01:54.220 --> 00:01:55.740
<v Teacher>Información.

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:57.260
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:01:57.260 --> 00:02:01.980
<v Teacher>What was you in the sense of I love you, I want you?

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:06.060
<v Teacher>And this is informal you this is used uh informally.

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:11.180
<v Teacher>How would you say then I don't want to oblige you?

00:02:11.180 --> 00:02:13.740
<v Teacher>So you might think, oh I don't know this.

00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:23.820
<v Teacher>It's very important sentences that we think we don't know to take them block by block and in this way we will realize we can say so much in Spanish that we would have assumed that we don't know how to say.

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:25.900
<v Teacher>So the first bit is I don't want

00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:28.159
<v Student>No quiero.

00:02:28.159 --> 00:02:29.360
<v Teacher>No quiero.

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:30.879
<v Teacher>To oblige.

00:02:30.879 --> 00:02:33.760
<v Teacher>So we look to see if we have obligation.

00:02:33.760 --> 00:02:34.959
<v Teacher>In English we have it, right?

00:02:34.959 --> 00:02:35.599
<v Teacher>It's a word.

00:02:35.599 --> 00:02:36.400
<v Teacher>It's legal.

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:37.680
<v Teacher>So how is that?

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:38.720
<v Teacher>Obligacion.

00:02:39.940 --> 00:02:42.260
<v Teacher>And to oblige then?

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:43.060
<v Student>Obligar.

00:02:43.060 --> 00:02:43.860
<v Teacher>Obligar.

00:02:44.099 --> 00:02:48.340
<v Teacher>So we don't want to jump from obliged to sticking R on it, you know?

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:49.700
<v Teacher>We want to take that long word

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:52.860
<v Teacher>obligation, obligacion, obligar.

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:55.099
<v Teacher>And then we find the the word in Spanish.

00:02:55.099 --> 00:02:59.340
<v Teacher>So I don't want, no quiero, to oblige you.

00:03:00.160 --> 00:03:02.959
<v Student>No quiero obligarte.

00:03:02.959 --> 00:03:03.440
<v Student>Good.

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:05.120
<v Teacher>No quiero obligarte.

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:06.640
<v Teacher>I don't want to oblige you.

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:08.239
<v Teacher>I don't want to make you do it.

00:03:08.239 --> 00:03:10.720
<v Teacher>So in English we we would say make you

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:17.020
<v Teacher>Maybe, maybe oblige sounds a little bit too formal, but in Spanish it's everyday language.

00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:19.740
<v Teacher>How would you say I don't want to provoke you?

00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:21.660
<v Teacher>I don't want to provoke you

00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:26.260
<v Student>No quiero provocarte.

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:26.740
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:29.060
<v Teacher>No quiero provocarte.

00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:34.500
<v Teacher>The word for it in Spanish is lo.

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:40.080
<v Teacher>Lo so how would you say I want to cancel it?

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:42.720
<v Student>Quiero cancelar lo.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:43.280
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:44.960
<v Teacher>Quiero cancelarlo.

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:47.440
<v Teacher>How would you say I want to regulate it?

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:51.000
<v Student>Quiero regularlo.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:51.799
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:51.799 --> 00:03:53.879
<v Teacher>I want to talk about this R.

00:03:53.879 --> 00:03:57.079
<v Teacher>An initial R, like in regular

00:03:57.620 --> 00:04:00.740
<v Teacher>In most Spanish dialects, it's a rolling ah.

00:04:00.740 --> 00:04:03.860
<v Teacher>You get this flick of the tongue regular real.

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:06.180
<v Teacher>We saw this as well in real real.

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:10.740
<v Teacher>Now if you can't make that sound, I don't want you to worry about it yet.

00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:15.159
<v Teacher>It's something that I couldn't pronounce it actually.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:20.440
<v Teacher>I couldn't pronounce it for a long time and it was really frustrating and I was trying to pronounce it

00:04:20.620 --> 00:04:23.900
<v Teacher>And when you're trying to pronounce it, your mouth gets tense.

00:04:23.900 --> 00:04:31.180
<v Teacher>And actually you need a very relaxed mouth to pronounce this R because you're kind of lifting your tongue up a little bit and letting the air flap it.

00:04:31.180 --> 00:04:32.379
<v Teacher>Now that's a muscle.

00:04:32.379 --> 00:04:35.259
<v Teacher>If it's tense, the air can't flap it.

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:35.819
<v Teacher>So I tried a very long time.

00:04:35.819 --> 00:04:37.659
<v Teacher>I got very frustrated and I gave up.

00:04:37.659 --> 00:04:40.699
<v Teacher>And then I was practicing Spanish in Peru.

00:04:40.699 --> 00:04:44.300
<v Teacher>One day I started speaking about race, which is arroz.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:53.840
<v Teacher>And the R came out all by itself and I was so excited and I was jumping up and down saying arroz, arroz, arroz and then I heard the green boy is hungry.

00:04:54.920 --> 00:05:00.920
<v Teacher>But uh it it I I my advice if you can't pronounce the sound is just to let it come.

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:05.000
<v Teacher>Uh the more you hear just because you want to pronounce it it's gonna come

00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:11.900
<v Teacher>So initial R or two R's together inside the word is going to pronounce this double R.

00:05:11.900 --> 00:05:14.780
<v Teacher>So the word for but in Spanish is pero

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:16.520
<v Student>Pero.

00:05:16.520 --> 00:05:17.880
<v Teacher>P-E-R-O.

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:21.080
<v Teacher>And the word for dog is perro.

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:22.440
<v Teacher>P-E-A-A-O

00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:23.900
<v Student>Pero.

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:24.700
<v Teacher>So that's the difference.

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:26.540
<v Teacher>You have numer A, pero.

00:05:26.540 --> 00:05:27.260
<v Student>Pero.

00:05:27.260 --> 00:05:31.020
<v Teacher>And it's a bit different to English because it's still kind of more pronounced.

00:05:31.020 --> 00:05:33.100
<v Teacher>You know, you're still using your tongue more there.

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:34.060
<v Teacher>Pero.

00:05:34.120 --> 00:05:44.120
<v Teacher>And then perro, you keep that in the same position that you are using to make that Spanish R which is kind of a little bit more pronounced than the rr rr English sound.

00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:47.479
<v Teacher>But you pass a little bit of air over it and you let that flick it

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:57.760
<v Teacher>Now like I said I don't want you to worry about if you can't pronounce this, there are even native Spanish speakers that can't pronounce this, so it's really something I don't want to inhibit anybody.

00:05:57.760 --> 00:06:02.080
<v Teacher>How do you think is uh salvation in Spanish?

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:04.000
<v Student>Salvacion.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:04.800
<v Teacher>Salvacion.

00:06:04.800 --> 00:06:08.080
<v Teacher>So how do you think it would be to save?

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:09.120
<v Student>Salvar.

00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:10.320
<v Teacher>Salvar.

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:16.080
<v Teacher>This word that we used for it, lo can also mean him.

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:18.420
<v Teacher>So how would you say I want to save him?

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:20.980
<v Student>Qiero salvarlo.

00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:21.540
<v Student>Good.

00:06:22.820 --> 00:06:24.660
<v Teacher>I want to save him.

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:27.460
<v Teacher>How would you say situation?

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:29.320
<v Teacher>Situation.

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:30.360
<v Teacher>Situation.

00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:30.919
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:30.919 --> 00:06:37.720
<v Teacher>Now if you turn that into a verb, you actually get to situate, to place, to put somewhere.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:39.479
<v Teacher>So how would that be?

00:06:40.759 --> 00:06:41.639
<v Student>Situar.

00:06:41.639 --> 00:06:42.599
<v Teacher>Situar.

00:06:42.599 --> 00:06:43.159
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:43.159 --> 00:06:45.560
<v Teacher>Participation.

00:06:45.560 --> 00:06:47.080
<v Student>Participacion.

00:06:47.080 --> 00:06:48.199
<v Teacher>Participacion

00:06:48.639 --> 00:06:59.840
<v Teacher>To participate So take it syllable by syllable this is very important so it doesn't become like a salad you know you want to take it syllable by syllable

00:07:00.840 --> 00:07:05.960
<v Student>Participation participacion participar

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:13.120
<v Teacher>So we want we must take it slowly.

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:19.360
<v Teacher>Sometimes we don't need to take it slowly, but we want to get in the habit of taking it slowly, dividing up syllable by syllable.

00:07:19.360 --> 00:07:21.600
<v Teacher>We want to install the correct process slowly.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:24.240
<v Teacher>We don't want to jump from participate.

00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:31.780
<v Teacher>to participar because maybe we end up putting some extra sound participar or something like this and we don't want to do this.

00:07:31.780 --> 00:07:33.620
<v Teacher>We want to take the long route

00:07:33.560 --> 00:07:39.400
<v Teacher>So for example, if you want to work out how to say to create in Spanish, you want to go through the long way.

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:41.240
<v Teacher>You want to go through creation.

00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:42.600
<v Student>Creacion.

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:43.240
<v Teacher>And then

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:44.740
<v Student>Crear.

00:07:44.740 --> 00:07:45.460
<v Student>Yeah, and that's it.

00:07:45.460 --> 00:07:46.500
<v Teacher>That's the verb in Spanish.

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:47.060
<v Teacher>Crear.

00:07:47.060 --> 00:07:48.740
<v Teacher>To create.

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:52.180
<v Teacher>How is to experiment?

00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:55.880
<v Student>So it's experimentation.

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:57.800
<v Student>Experimentacion.

00:07:58.840 --> 00:07:59.960
<v Student>Experimentar.

00:07:59.960 --> 00:08:00.920
<v Student>Yeah, that's it.

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:01.960
<v Teacher>Experimentar.

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:04.440
<v Teacher>And this also means to experience.

00:08:04.220 --> 00:08:13.100
<v Teacher>to experiment and to experience, which is a little bit of wisdom that I really like there from Spanish because your experience is like an experiment.

00:08:13.100 --> 00:08:16.060
<v Teacher>If you think that your relationship with experience

00:08:16.340 --> 00:08:17.700
<v Teacher>is scientific.

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:21.220
<v Teacher>You look what happens and you learn from it, or at least you should.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:28.820
<v Teacher>So in Spanish there is a suggestion of that in the fact that these words are the same to experience and to experiment.

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:30.440
<v Teacher>is the same verb experimentar.

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:31.960
<v Teacher>The nouns are different.

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:34.919
<v Teacher>Experience is experiencia.

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:37.560
<v Teacher>Experiment is experimento.

00:08:37.440 --> 00:08:39.919
<v Teacher>But the verb, the act, is the same verb.

00:08:39.919 --> 00:08:40.880
<v Teacher>Experimentar.

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:42.800
<v Teacher>Actually this gives us another nice rule.

00:08:43.040 --> 00:08:44.160
<v Teacher>Experience.

00:08:44.160 --> 00:08:45.200
<v Teacher>Experiencia

00:08:45.839 --> 00:08:54.319
<v Teacher>If we have a word that ends in enzo ants, we can change ens to ancia and ans to ancia, and we will get the word in Spanish.

00:08:54.319 --> 00:08:56.079
<v Teacher>Difference.

00:08:56.079 --> 00:08:57.279
<v Student>Differencia.

00:08:57.279 --> 00:08:57.839
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:57.839 --> 00:08:59.360
<v Teacher>Influence.

00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:01.779
<v Student>Influencia.

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:04.820
<v Teacher>Existence.

00:09:04.820 --> 00:09:06.100
<v Student>Existencia.

00:09:06.100 --> 00:09:06.740
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:07.700
<v Teacher>Consistence

00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:17.339
<v Student>In consistence, inconsistencia

00:09:21.839 --> 00:09:23.360
<v Student>Incongruencia.

